Routing is a critical component in ASP.NET MVC that enables clean, readable URL mapping. The RouteConfig class defines route templates that match incoming URLs to specific controller actions. When a request arrives, the routing system examines the URL and determines the appropriate controller and action method to handle the request.

A typical route configuration might look like this:
```csharp
public class RouteConfig
{
    public static void RegisterRoutes(RouteCollection routes)
    {
        routes.MapRoute(
            name: "Default",
            url: "{controller}/{action}/{id}",
            defaults: new { controller = "Home", action = "Index", id = UrlParameter.Optional }
        );
    }
}

Controllers are fundamental to the MVC design pattern, responsible for handling user interactions, processing input, and coordinating between the Model and View. They receive user requests, perform necessary data operations, and determine which view should be displayed.

A simple controller example demonstrates its core responsibilities:
```csharp
public class UserController : Controller
{
    public ActionResult Profile(int userId)
    {
        var user = _userService.GetUserById(userId);
        return View(user);
    }
}

The request lifecycle in ASP.NET MVC is a well-defined sequence of events that begins when a request is received and ends when a response is sent back. Key stages include routing, controller initialization, action method execution, and view rendering.

A typical lifecycle flow can be illustrated with pipeline interceptors:
```csharp
public class CustomActionFilter : IActionFilter
{
    public void OnActionExecuting(ActionExecutingContext filterContext)
    {
        // Perform operations before action method execution
    }

    public void OnActionExecuted(ActionExecutedContext filterContext)
    {
        // Perform operations after action method execution
    }
}

Action methods are fundamental to ASP.NET MVC's request processing model. They are responsible for receiving HTTP requests, processing user input, interacting with models, and determining which view to render or data to return. Each action is typically decorated with HTTP method attributes like [HttpGet] or [HttpPost] to specify its behavior. A typical action method might look like this:

```csharp
public ActionResult Details(int id)
{
    var model = _repository.GetById(id);
    return View(model);
}
```

Razor simplifies view creation by providing a clean, intuitive syntax for embedding C# code within HTML. Its primary advantages include minimal syntax overhead and seamless integration with ASP.NET MVC. A typical Razor view demonstrates its inline code capabilities:

```cshtml
@model User
<h1>Welcome, @Model.Name!</h1>
@if (Model.IsAdmin) {
    <p>You have administrator privileges.</p>
}
```

ASP.NET MVC provides multiple mechanisms for transferring data between Controllers and Views. ViewData and ViewBag are dynamic dictionaries, while strongly-typed models offer type safety. Here's an example demonstrating data transfer:

```csharp
public ActionResult Index()
{
    // Using ViewData
    ViewData["Title"] = "Welcome";

    // Using ViewBag
    ViewBag.Message = "Hello, World!";

    // Using strongly-typed model
    var model = new UserViewModel { Name = "John" };
    return View(model);
}
```

Model Binding is a crucial aspect of ASP.NET MVC that simplifies data transfer between web forms and business objects. Value providers extract data from various sources like form fields, query strings, and route data. The default model binder uses type conversion and naming conventions to match request data to model properties. Developers can customize this process by creating custom model binders or using attributes like [Bind].

Example of a simple model binding scenario:
```csharp
public ActionResult Create(UserViewModel model)
{
    if (ModelState.IsValid)
    {
        // Model is automatically populated from request data
        _userService.CreateUser(model);
        return RedirectToAction("Index");
    }
    return View(model);
}
```

The ViewStart.cshtml file is typically located in the Views folder and provides a way to set default view-level configurations. It is particularly useful for setting a consistent layout across multiple views without repeating code. When multiple ViewStart files exist in nested directories, they are applied hierarchically, allowing for more granular configurations.

Example of a typical ViewStart file:
```csharp
@{
    Layout = "~/Views/Shared/_DefaultLayout.cshtml";
}
```

Partial Views and View Components serve different rendering purposes in ASP.NET MVC. Partial Views are simpler and typically used for small, reusable UI fragments, while View Components offer more flexibility and can include complex logic. View Components can have their own model, logic, and async rendering capabilities.

Example of a Partial View:
```csharp
@await Html.PartialAsync("_UserProfilePartial", userModel)

// View Component Example
@await Component.InvokeAsync("ShoppingCart")
```
